value.value: A flower (PO:0009046) that includes as part a single carpel (PO:0009030) or a gynoecium (PO:0009062), but the androecium (PO:0009061) is absent or has aborted during development.
A flower (PO:0009046) that includes as part an androecium (PO:0009061), and the gynoecium (PO:0009062) is absent or has aborted during development.
An inflorescence (PO:0009049) that includes as part only staminate flowers (PO:0025600).
A gametophyte development stage (PO:0028003) during which a microgametophyte (PO:0025280) develops.
A portion of plant substance (PO:0025161) that consists of a complex mixture of organic aromatic compounds such as mono-, sesqui-, and diterpenoids.

definition.value: Plant resins are often produced by Gymnosperms but not restricted to those plants. In the conifers, plant resins are constitutively and inducibly produced through the secretory activity of resin cells (PO:0025604), and can be exuded through a resin canal (PO:0005665) to a site of injury or predator attack.

value.value: A plant epidermal cell (PO:0004013) that secretes plant resin (PO:0025603), and may line resin canals (PO:0005665) and/or be associated with resin blisters (or cysts).
An abscission zone (PO:0000146) that forms as a swelling or joint on a fruit pedicel (PO:0030114).
A plant cell (PO:0009002) that is either part of a multicellular whole plant (PO:0000003) 'in vivo' or a unicellular organism 'in natura' (i.e. part of a natural environment).

definition.value: A native plant cell is one that is not grown or maintained in vitro, nor part of an in vitro plant structure (PO:0000004).

value.value: A shoot system (PO:0009006) that has as parts only vegetative tissues and organs.
An abscission zone (PO:0000146) that forms as a swelling or joint on a flower pedicel (PO:0030113).
A portion of plant tissue (PO:0009007) that forms a tough, protective outer layer on a shoot axis and includes as parts a shoot axis hypodermis (PO:0005057) and a shoot axis epidermis (PO:0000112).
A portion of hypodermis (PO:0005051) that is part of a stem cortex (PO:0025612).
A portion of shoot axis tegument layer (PO:0025609) that a tough, protective outer layer on a stem (PO:0009047) and includes as parts a stem hypodermis (PO:0025610) and a stem epidermis (PO:0025178).
A portion of shoot axis cortex (PO:0000223) that is part of a stem (PO:0009047).
A petiole (PO:0020038) that is sclerified and persistent.

definition.value: The petiole (PO:0020038) abcisses longitudinally and the leaf lamina (PO:0020039) withers.

value.value: A portion of plant tissue (PO:0009007) which is a small ball of cells born on a thallus (PO:0030027) and is involved in asexual reproduction.
A collective leaf structure (PO:0025022) consisting of a group of rosette leaves (PO:0000014), generally borne at the base of the plant, that are separated by very short stem internodes (PO:0020142).
A cardinal organ part (PO:0025001) which is a short, abrupt, flexible point at the apex of the lemma (PO:0009037).
A portion of carpel epidermis (PO:0025096) that covers the abaxial surface of a carpel (PO:0009030).

definition.value: The abaxial surface is the one which is furthest from the plant axis.

value.value: A portion of carpel epidermis (PO:0025096) that covers the adaxial surface of a carpel (PO:0009030).

definition.value: The adaxial surface is the one which is closest to the plant axis.

value.value: A cardinal organ part (PO:0025001) that is the edge of a laminar portion of a leaf sheath (PO:0020104) and the area immediately internally adjacent to it.
A primary xylem vessel (PO:0025450) which is part of the metaxylem (PO:0000372).

definition.value: Metaxylem vessels are composed of metaxylem vessel members (elements; PO:0025622).

value.value: A primary xylem tracheid (PO:0025446) that is part of the metaxylem (PO:0000372).
A primary xylem vessel member (PO:0025448) that is part of the metaxylem (PO:0000372).
A first order infructescence axis (PO:0025244) in an ear infructescence (PO:0025597) that bears kernels (i.e. caryopsis fruit; PO:0030104).
A ground tissue cell (PO:0025030) that is part of a portion of endodermis (PO:0000252).
An initial cell (PO:0004011) that produces cortex (PO:0005708) and endodermis (PO:0000252).
A multi-tissue plant structure (PO:0025496) that develops in response to a biotic stress (PSO:0000011).
A whole plant development stage (PO:0007033) that has as primary participant a whole plant (PO:0000003) during the interval between fertilization (or apogamy) and death.

definition.value: A whole plant (PO:0000003) in the sporophyte development stage usually has twice the chromosome complement of a plant in the gametophytic phase, but may not in the case of apogamy. Examples of apogamy include both naturally occurring instances (such as sporophytes arising form haploid cells as in bryophytes or ferns) as well as in vitro instances (such as haploid embryo culture or in vitro fusion of non-gamete cells or protoplasts). During the sporophyte development stage, a plant may produce meiospores by meiosis.

value.value: A whole plant development stage (PO:0007033) that has as primary participant a whole plant (PO:0000003) during the interval between meiosis or apospory and the time that the whole plant ceases to exist.

definition.value: In bryophytes and pteridophytes, a gametophytic phase may begin without meiosis by apospory. This usually occurs when damage to a plant in the sporophytic phase leads directly to the growth of a plant that is in the gametophyte development stage but bears the chromosome complement that would normally be found in the sporophyte development stage (PO:0028002). A whole plant in the gametophyte development stage usually has half the chromosome complement of a plant in the sporophyte development stage, but not in the case of apospory. A whole plant in the gametophyte development stage may cease to exist by death at any point in its development. In seed plants, the whole plant in the gametophyte development stage may cease to exists through transformation, such as when pollen (PO:0025281) releases its pollen sperm cells (PO:0025121) or when a plant embryo (PO:0009009) begins to develop within an embryo sac (PO:0025074) of an angiosperm. During the gametophytic phase, a plant may produce gametes (PO:0025006) by mitosis.

value.value: A shoot axis apex (PO:0000037) that is part of a branch (PO:0025073).

A collective plant organ structure (PO:0025007) which is a cluster of gametophore branches (PO:0030021) or non-vascular leaves (PO:0025075) at the top of the gametophore axis (PO:0030020), forming a tuft.

definition.value: In the moss genus Sphagnum, the gametophore coma is always composed of gametophore branches, but in all other mosses, it is composed of non-vascular leaves.

value.value: A chlorenchyma cell that is part of a chloronema and has cross walls of adjacent cells that are perpendicular to the protonema axis.

definition.value: A chloronema cell contains many well-developed chloroplasts.

value.value: A chlorenchyma cell that is part of a caulonema and has cross walls of adjacent cells that are oblique to the protonema axis.

definition.value: A caulonema cell contains fewer, less well-developed chloroplasts than a chloronema cell.

value.value: A portion of chlorenchyma tissue that develops directly from a spore and grows by division of an apical cell to form filaments that are one cell wide and dichotomously branching.

definition.value: The protonema is the first structure that develops in the gametophytic phase of mosses, some other bryophytes, and leptosporangiate ferns. The term protonema is also used to refer to the phase of development in which protonemal tissue is produced (see PO:0030006 protonema phase). In some species of moss, the protonema is perennial. A protonema may develop from sporophytic tissue during apospory.

value.value: A portion of protonema tissue that consists of only chloronema cells.

definition.value: Generally, the development of chloronema precedes the development of caulonema. Only the caulonema, and not the chloronema, initiates gametophore buds.

value.value: A portion of protonema tissue that consists of only caulonema cells.

definition.value: Generally, the development of caulonema follows the development of chloronema. Only the caulonema, and not the chloronema, initiates gametophore buds.

value.value: A gametophyte development stage during which a gametophyte undergoes filamentous growth and that succeeds spore germination and precedes a thalloid development stage (planar growth) or gametophore development stage.

definition.value: The protonema phase ends with the development of gametophores in mosses, some other bryophytes, and leptosporangiate ferns and with the development of a thallus in other bryophytes, although protonema tissue may persist of continue to develop after this.

value.value: A single meristematic cell (PO:0004010) at the tip of a plant structure where apical growth occurs.

definition.value: Apical cells occur only at the tip of a shoot axis apex, leaf apex, root apex, thallus apex, or protonema in bryophytes and some pteridophytes. Apical growth results from division of a single meristematic cell located at the tip of an apical meristem or plant organ, rather than from a population of meristematic cells located at the tip of an apical meristem. The apical cell may be tetrahedral shaped, with three (in shoots) or four (in roots) cutting faces, or wedge-shaped (lenticular) with two cutting faces (in non-vascular leaves or thalli). An apical cell may be established upon germination of a spore or upon the first cell division of an embryo, or later.

value.value: A sporophyte meristematic apical cell that is part of a root tip.

definition.value: Occurs in the sporophytic phase of pteridophytes.

value.value: A meristematic apical cell that is part of a shoot system.

definition.value: May occur in shoot axes or leaves of bryophytes or ferns.

value.value: A shoot meristematic apical cell that is part of a shoot apex.

definition.value: Divides to produces leaf initial cells (if leaves are present) and other stem or branch tissues.

value.value: A shoot meristematic apical cell that is part of a leaf apex.

definition.value: Occurs in the non-vascular leaves of bryophytes and the vascular leaves of some ferns. Only in plants where leaf growth is apical.

value.value: A leaf meristematic apical cell that is part of the leaf apex of a vascular leaf.

definition.value: Occurs in vascular leaves of some ferns in their sporophytic phase.

value.value: A leaf meristematic apical cell (PO:0030011) that is part of a leaf apex of a non-vascular leaf.

definition.value: Occurs in the non-vascular leaves of bryophytes, which grow by division of a single, wedge-shaped apical cell with two cutting faces.

value.value: An apical cell that is part of a whole plant in the gametophytic phase.

definition.value: Occurs bryophytes and pteridophytes.

value.value: A meristematic apical cell that is part of a whole plant in the sporophytic phase.

definition.value: Occurs in pteridophytes and the sporophyte of bryophytes.

value.value: A shoot axis meristematic apical cell at the tip of a seta.

definition.value: Ceases being an apical cell when the sporangium begins to develop.

value.value: A plant anatomical space that is the opening on the apical end of a spore capsule.

definition.value: May be covered by a peristome.

value.value: A shoot system (PO:0009006) that consists of the shoot axes (PO:0025029) and non-vascular leaves (PO:0025075) of a plant in the gametophyte development stage (PO:0028003) .

definition.value: A gametophore is the leafy part of the gametophyte of mosses and leafy liverworts, excluding the protonema. Develop from buds that form on the protonema. Antheridia and archegonia arise on the gametophore.
